DAY 12 - INHERITANCE (extends)

Today's Goal: At the end of this lesson, you'll understand why extends exists. We will NOT learn super today. One step at a time.

Imagine Your Father 👨

Suppose your father has

Eyes 👀
Nose 👃
Hair 💇

You also have

Eyes 👀
Nose 👃
Hair 💇

Did you create them yourself?

😂 No.

You inherited them from your parents.

This is called:

Inheritance

Meaning:

Getting something from your parent.

Another Example

Imagine Animal.

Every animal can

Eat 🍖
Sleep 😴

Now Dog is also an Animal.

Can Dog eat?

✅ Yes.

Can Dog sleep?

✅ Yes.

Can Dog bark?

✅ Yes.

Notice:

Dog has

Eat
Sleep

from Animal.

And

Bark

from itself.

Java Version

Parent class

class Animal {

    void eat() {
        System.out.println("Animal is eating");
    }

    void sleep() {
        System.out.println("Animal is sleeping");
    }

}

Dog

class Dog extends Animal {

    void bark() {
        System.out.println("Dog is barking");
    }

}

Most important word:

extends

Read it like English:

Dog extends Animal

↓

Dog is a type of Animal.
Visual
        Animal
       /      \
   eat()     sleep()

          ▲
          |
      extends
          |
        Dog
          |
       bark()

Dog gets

eat()

sleep()

FREE.

No need to write them again.

Main Method
public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Dog d = new Dog();

        d.eat();

        d.sleep();

        d.bark();

    }

}

Output

Animal is eating
Animal is sleeping
Dog is barking
Wait...

We never wrote

eat()

inside Dog.

Then why did it work?

Because

extends

copied the parent's abilities.

Think of it as:

Dog

↓

inherits

↓

Animal
Another Example

Parent

class Vehicle {

    void start() {
        System.out.println("Vehicle Started");
    }

}

Child

class Car extends Vehicle {

    void drive() {
        System.out.println("Car is Driving");
    }

}

Main

Car c = new Car();

c.start();

c.drive();

Output

Vehicle Started
Car is Driving

Again

Car never had

start()

It got it from

Vehicle.

Real Life

Imagine your company.

Employee has

ID Card
Salary
Login

Developer is also an Employee.

So Developer automatically has

ID Card
Salary
Login

PLUS

Developer has

Coding
Java
class Employee {

    void login() {
        System.out.println("Login");
    }

}
class Developer extends Employee {

    void code() {
        System.out.println("Coding");
    }

}

Developer can do

login();
code();
Why Do We Use Inheritance?

Without inheritance

class Dog {

    eat()

    sleep()

    bark()

}
class Cat {

    eat()

    sleep()

    meow()

}
class Lion {

    eat()

    sleep()

    roar()

}

You write

eat()
sleep()

again and again.

With inheritance

Animal

↓

eat()

sleep()

Dog

↓

bark()

Cat

↓

meow()

Lion

↓

roar()


No repeated code.

Professional.

